After more debugging, I think I found a bug in the activity code.  In the ActivityPersistanceHelper.java (in the org.eclipse.ui.workbench plug-in) has the following method

protected void loadEnabledStates(Set previouslyEnabledActivities, Set activityIdsToProcess) {
.
.
.
     for (Iterator i = activityIdsToProcess.iterator(); i
                .hasNext();) {
            String activityId = (String) i.next();
            String preferenceKey = createPreferenceKey(activityId);
		try {
                IActivity activity = activityManager.getActivity(activityId);
                if ("".equals(store.getDefaultString(preferenceKey))) { 
                	store.setDefault(preferenceKey, activity
							.isDefaultEnabled());
                	store.setValue(preferenceKey, activity.isEnabled());

                }				

            } catch (NotDefinedException e) {
                // can't happen - we're iterating over defined activities
           }

            if (store.getBoolean(preferenceKey)) {
            	System.err.println("added"); //$NON-NLS-1$
				enabledActivities.add(activityId);
			} else {
				System.err.println("not added"); //$NON-NLS-1$
				enabledActivities.remove(activityId);
			}

Basically the problem is following

when we don't use -Dosgi.signedcontent.support=true , the store.setDefault() from the above method will get called, so the "UIActivities.org.eclipse.equinox.security.ui.defaultPolicyActivity" property will set to false in the DefaultPreferences.  Somehow, this also set same the property to TRUE in the InstancePreferences object (I still don't understand how that happens...)

I debugged into the store.getBoolean(preferenceKey) methods and found out the Preference Service returns two IEclipsePreference and array index 0 is InstancePreferences.  So the security activity is still added to the enabled set even though -Dosgi.signedcontent.support=true vm is not set.

So the fix is to replace the store.setDefault(preferenceKey, activity.isEnabled()) with store.setValue(preferenceKey, activity.isEnabled());
